<p data-start="27" data-end="307" class="">A <strong data-start="29" data-end="40">trigger</strong> is a special type of stored procedure in a <strong data-start="84" data-end="92">DBMS</strong> that automatically executes when a specified event occurs in a table, such as <strong data-start="171" data-end="200">INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE</strong>. Triggers help in maintaining <strong data-start="231" data-end="286">data integrity, logging, validation, and automation</strong> of repetitive tasks.</p>
<hr data-start="309" data-end="312" class="">
<h2 data-start="314" data-end="341" class=""><strong data-start="317" data-end="341">📌 Types of Triggers</strong></h2>
<ol data-start="342" data-end="767">
<li data-start="342" data-end="416" class="">
<p data-start="345" data-end="416" class=""><strong data-start="345" data-end="364">Before Triggers</strong> → Executes <strong data-start="376" data-end="386">before</strong> the specified event occurs.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="417" data-end="489" class="">
<p data-start="420" data-end="489" class=""><strong data-start="420" data-end="438">After Triggers</strong> → Executes <strong data-start="450" data-end="459">after</strong> the specified event occurs.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="490" data-end="581" class="">
<p data-start="493" data-end="581" class=""><strong data-start="493" data-end="516">Instead of Triggers</strong> → Used in <strong data-start="527" data-end="536">views</strong>, replacing the default action of an event.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="582" data-end="655" class="">
<p data-start="585" data-end="655" class=""><strong data-start="585" data-end="607">Row-Level Triggers</strong> → Fires <strong data-start="616" data-end="641">once per affected row</strong> in a table.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="656" data-end="767" class="">
<p data-start="659" data-end="767" class=""><strong data-start="659" data-end="687">Statement-Level Triggers</strong> → Fires <strong data-start="696" data-end="722">once per SQL statement</strong>, regardless of how many rows are affected.</p>
</li>
</ol>
